===Verb===
{{en-verb|bleeds|bleeding|bled}}
{{rfc|en|Malory quote is malformatted and is Middle English (enm) - RFV for the New English (en) sense?)}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive|of a person or animal}} To [[lose]] [[blood]] through an [[injured]] [[blood vessel]].
#: ''If her nose '''bleeds''', try to use ice.''
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[let]] or [[draw]] [[blood]] from.
#* '''1979''', Octavia Butler, ''Kindred'':
#*: "What did they die of?" I asked.<br/>"Fevers. The doctor came and '''bled''' them and purged them, but they still died."<br/>"He '''bled''' and purged babies?"<br/>"They were two and three. He said it would break the fever. And it did. But they ... they died anyway."
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[take]] large amounts of [[money]] from.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To steadily lose (something vital).
#: ''The company was '''bleeding''' talent.''
# {{lb|en|intransitive|of an ink or dye}} To [[spread]] from the intended location and [[stain]] the surrounding [[cloth]] or [[paper]].
#: {{ux|en|[[ink trap|Ink trap]]s [[counteract]] '''bleeding'''.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[remove]] [[air]] bubbles from a [[pipe]] containing [[fluid]]s.
# {{lb|en|obsolete|transitive}} To bleed on; to make bloody.
#* {{RQ:Mlry MrtArthr1|VIII}}
#*: And so Sir Trystrames '''bledde''' bothe the over-shete and the neyther-shete, and the pylowes and the hede-shete
# {{lb|en|intransitive|copulative}} To show one's group loyalty by showing (its associated color) in one's blood.
#: ''He was a devoted Vikings fan: he '''bled''' purple.''
# To lose sap, gum, or juice.
#: ''A tree or a vine '''bleeds''' when tapped or wounded.''
# To issue forth, or drop, like blood from an incision.
#* {{rfdatek|en|Alexander Pope}}
#*: For me the balm shall '''bleed'''.
# {{lb|en|phonology|transitive|of a phonological rule}} To destroy the environment where another phonological rule would have applied.
#: ''Labialization '''bleeds''' palatalization.''

